'''''Bedlam''''' is a [[TRS-80]] based [[text adventure]] game written for the TRS-80 by Robert Arnstein and released by [[Tandy Corporation]] in 1982.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pitre|first1=Boisy|title=CoCo: The Colorful History of Tandy's Underdog Computer|date=2014|publisher=CRC Press|location=Boca Raton, Florida|page=45}}</ref> It was ported to the [[TRS-80 Color Computer]].<ref name="boyle">{{cite web |last1=Boyle |first1=L. Curtis |title=Bedlam |url=http://www.lcurtisboyle.com/nitros9/bedlam.html |website=Tandy Color Computer Games}}</ref> The object of the game is to escape a [[lunatic asylum]]. There are several ways to escape but only one random exit is active each time the game is loaded.

== Gameplay ==
[[File:Bedlam opening screen.png|thumb|right|Opening screen|alt=A computer screen which displays only text about waking up from a very bad dream]]
The game is text only. Players move through the asylum by typing simple instructions using a [[verb]]-[[noun]] command such as, "go north" or "get the key". There are [[Non-player character|NPCs]] such as Houdini and Picasso that can be either helpful or an obstacle.

